\begin_layout Subsection
Metric Spaces and the Baire Category Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Definition 8.2.1.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, a function 
\begin_inset Formula $d:X\times X\rightarrow\RR$
\end_inset

 is a metric on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

 :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(i) 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x,y)\geq0$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x,y)=0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=y$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x,y)=d(y,x)$
\end_inset

, and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(iii) for all 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in X,d(x,y)\leq d(x,z)+d(z,y)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A metric space is a set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 together with a metric 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Definition 8.2.2.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 be a metric space.
 A sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{n}\right)\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 converges to an element 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

 there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\NN$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $d\left(x_{n},x\right)<\epsilon$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Definition 8.2.3.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 in a metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 is a Cauchy sequence if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

 there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\NN$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $d\left(x_{m},x_{n}\right)<\epsilon$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n\geq N$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Definition 8.2.4.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 is complete if every Cauchy sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 converges to an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Definition 8.2.5.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 be a metric space.
 A function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\rightarrow\RR$
\end_inset

 is continuous at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

 there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|f(x)-f(y)|<\epsilon$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x,y)<\delta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Definition 8.2.6.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

 and an element 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in the metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

-neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the set 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\epsilon}(x)=\{y\in X:d(x,y)<\epsilon\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Definition 8.2.7.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A subset 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 of a metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 is compact if every sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 has a convergent subsequence that converges to a limit in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Definition 8.2.8.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 of a metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

, the closure 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{E}$
\end_inset

 is the union of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 together with its limit points.
 The interior of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 and is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E^{\circ}=\left\{ x\in E:\text{ there exists }V_{\epsilon}(x)\subseteq E\right\} .
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Definition 8.2.9.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A set 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 is dense in the metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{A}=X$
\end_inset

 A subset 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 of a metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 is nowhere-dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{E}^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 is empty.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Exercise 8.2.12.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is a subspace of a metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

, show that 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is nowhere-dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{E}^{c}$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Theorem 8.2.10.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,d)$
\end_inset

 be a complete metric space, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ O_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 be a countable collection of dense, open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcap_{n=1}^{\infty}O_{n}$
\end_inset

 is not empty.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Theorem 8.2.11 (Baire Category Theorem).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A complete metric space is not the union of a countable collection of nowhere-de
nse sets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Theorem 8.2.12.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D=\left\{ f\in C[0,1]:f^{\prime}(x)\text{ exists for some }x\in[0,1]\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

is a set of first category in 
\begin_inset Formula $C[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fourier Series
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Theorem 8.3.2 (Riemann-Lebesgue Lemma).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)$
\end_inset

 is continuous on 
\begin_inset Formula $(-\pi,\pi]$
\end_inset

.
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}h(x)\sin(nx)dx\rightarrow0\quad\text{ and }\quad\int_{-\pi}^{\pi}h(x)\cos(nx)dx\rightarrow0
\]

\end_inset

as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike power series, Fourier series can converge conditionally.
 This makes them less robust, perhaps, but more versatile and capable of
 more interesting behavior.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 1966, Lennart Carleson proved (via an extremely complicated argument)
 that the Fourier series for such a function converges pointwise at every
 point in the domain excluding possibly a set of measure zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are examples of continuous functions with Fourier series that diverge
 at uncountably many points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is an example due to A.
 Kolmogorov (1903–1987) of a Lebesgue-integrable function where the Fourier
 series fails to converge at any point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Theorem 8.3.3.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 be continuous on 
\begin_inset Formula $(-\pi,\pi]$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{N}(x)$
\end_inset

 be the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 th partial sum of the Fourier series described in equation (7), where the
 coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(b_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 are given by equations (9) and (10).
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{N\rightarrow\infty}S_{N}(x)=f(x)
\]

\end_inset

pointwise at any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in(-\pi,\pi]$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime}(x)$
\end_inset

 exists.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Theorem 8.3.4 (Fejér's Theorem).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{N}(x)$
\end_inset

 be the Nth partial sum of the Fourier series for a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $(-\pi,\pi]$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma_{N}(x)=\frac{1}{N+1}\sum_{n=0}^{N}S_{N}(x).
\]

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous on 
\begin_inset Formula $(-\pi,\pi]$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{N}(x)\rightarrow f(x)$
\end_inset

 uniformly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Theorem 8.3.5 (Weierstrass Approximation Theorem).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a continuous function on a closed interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

, then there exists a sequence of polynomials that converges uniformly to
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea of approximation permeates the entire subject.
 Every real number can be approximated with rational ones.
 The value of an infinite sum is approximated with partial sums, and the
 value of a continuous function can be approximated with its values nearby.
 A function is differentiable when a straight line is a good approximation
 to the curve, and it is integrable when finite sums of rectangles are a
 good approximation to the area under the curve.
 Now, we learn that every continuous function can be approximated arbitrarily
 well with a polynomial.
 In every case, the approximating objects are tangible and well-understood,
 and the issue is how well these properties survive the limiting process.
 By viewing the different infinities of mathematics through pathways crafted
 out of finite objects, Weierstrass and the other founders of analysis created
 a paradigm for how to extend the scope of mathematical explo- ration deep
 into territory previously unattainable.
 Although our journey ends here, the road is long and continues to be written.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
A Construction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\RR$
\end_inset

 From 
\begin_inset Formula $\QQ$
\end_inset


\end_layout

